creator: Various
description:
LibriVox recording of Short Poetry Collection 140 by Various.
Read in English by Chris Pyle; Winston Tharp; Bruce Kachuk; Kangaroo692; Shakira Searle; DomBombadil; Larry Wilson; Ed W.; Andani Thakhathi; Bruce T. Filbeck; Algy Pug; Nathan Breisath; Alisson Veldhuis; Phil Schempf; Gemma L Myers; Vespero; Andrew Olson; Son of the Exiles; Hilary Hew
This is a collection of 32 poems read by LibriVox volunteers for January 2015. This collection includes the following: The Beacons, by Charles Baudelaire The Black Vulture, by George Sterling An Evening Thought - Written At Sea, by Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr. Excelsior, by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow From One Who Stays, by Amy Lowell Gethsemane, by Rudyard Kipling Godly sorrow arising from the sufferings of Christ, by Isaac Watts The Hermit, by George William Russell If Men only Understood, by James Allen The Kiss, by Robert Graves The Man Who Couldn't Save, by Edgar A. Guest Midnight, by Alfred, Lord Tennyson The Oak, by Alfred, Lord Tennyson The Other Fellow, by Edgar A. Guest Passer Mortuus Est, by Edna St. Vincent Millay The Pastime of the Queen of Fairies, by Margaret Cavendish, Duchess of Newcastle Poem VII (When smoke stood up from Ludlow), by A. E. Housman The Present Crisis, by James Russell Lowell The Prisoner for Debt, by John Greenleaf Whittier Religion, by Paul Laurence Dunbar Sic Vita, by Henry King Silent Noon, by Dante Gabriel Rossetti The Snow Man, by Wallace Stevens Song (Go and Catch a Falling Star), by John Donne Sonnet II (Time does not bring relief), by Edna St. Vincent Millay To A Caged Lion, by Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr. To Sleep, by John Keats The Voiceless, by Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr. Vulgar Fractions, by C. J. Dennis When You Know a Fellow, by Edgar A. Guest The Word of an Engineer, by James Weldon Johnson You Felons on Trial in Courts, by Walt Whitman
For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording.

For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org.
